Split Train-Validation-Test¶

In [7]:
# Split into train and validation sets

PATH = '/content/data'
BATCH_SIZE = 32
IMG_SIZE = (160, 160)

# Split into train/test
# by default, class names are infered, and converted to int
train_dataset = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(directory = PATH,
                                                            validation_split=0.3,
                                                            subset='training',
                                                            shuffle=True,
                                                            seed=1,
                                                            batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
                                                            image_size=IMG_SIZE)

validation_dataset = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(directory = PATH,
                                                                 validation_split=0.3,
                                                                 subset='validation',
                                                                 shuffle=True,
                                                                 seed=1,
                                                                 batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
                                                                 image_size=IMG_SIZE)

# Create test dataset from validation dataset
val_batches = tf.data.experimental.cardinality(validation_dataset)
test_dataset = validation_dataset.take(val_batches // 5)
validation_dataset = validation_dataset.skip(val_batches // 5)

Data augmentation¶

In [13]:
# Create a data augmentation model
data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.layers.RandomFlip('horizontal_and_vertical', seed=0),
  tf.keras.layers.RandomRotation(0.2, seed=0),
  tf.keras.layers.RandomContrast(0.5, seed=0),
  tf.keras.layers.RandomZoom(height_factor=0.7, width_factor=0.2, seed=0)
])

# use functional API to create the entire model, including the input pipeline and model
inputs = tf.keras.Input(shape=IMG_SHAPE) # shape can follow image shape
x = data_augmentation(inputs)
x = preprocess_input(x)
x = base_model(x, training=False)
x = global_average_layer(x)
x = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
outputs = prediction_layer(x)
model = tf.keras.Model(inputs, outputs)
model.summary()

Fine tune¶

Goal: Train the higher level convolutional layer. This is to allow high level features to be adapted to our own dataset.

In [36]:
# Check how many layers are in the base model
print("Number of layers in the base model: ", len(base_model.layers))

Number of layers in the base model:  175
In [38]:
# Unfreeze base model
base_model.trainable = True

# Fine-tune from this layer onwards
# Since the base model is very big and the current accuracy is already 99.8%, let's just fine tune the last layer
fine_tune_at = 174

# Freeze all the layers before the `fine_tune_at` layer
for layer in base_model.layers[:fine_tune_at]:
  layer.trainable = False

# Compile using lower learning rate
# using RMSprop to have a more gradual learning
model.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
              optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.RMSprop(learning_rate=base_learning_rate/10),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

model.summary()
